And from the results of this year's exams, we see that languages are the top-performing languages for independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who have studied foreign languages have achieved a high A grade.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of pupils have achieved A in Chinese, with the same score being achieved by 72% of those studying German, 69% of those teaching French and 63% of those studying Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland regard foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Currently, languages are given the same treatment as natural and mathematical disciplines (scientific, technological, engineering and mathematical) in and beyond the programmes of independent schools.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK Employment and Labour Skills Commission showed that 17% of the reasons why employers find it difficult to find employees indicated insufficient language skills.
Therefore, learning foreign languages is becoming increasingly compulsory in order to prepare young people for future careers.
More and more jobs require foreign language proficiency, which makes these skills essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career chosen, if a person mastered a foreign language, he would have a real advantage in the future, since he possessed such a skill that lasted a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person on the same page as the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4000 UK adult citizens in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to speak a language, with French being the only language whose level of proficiency reaches a double digit rate of 15%.
That's why investing in language learning today is important for children now.
The ability to speak several languages, especially those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, every school will be different in terms of the languages taught.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered more important for the UK in the future by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be enough languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are experts in their field.
Independent schools in Scotland are determined to provide an educational environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed in life, no matter what the future holds.
At present, there is no denying that in a global business environment languages continue to play an incredibly important role in the future of any country, which must be taken into account in the education system.
And indeed, modern languages should really be considered as international communication skills.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, together with diversity and excellent quality, to young people in Scotland.
It's got to be done.
