The official said the problem had grown bigger over time as the old ships were decommissioned but not provided with new ones.
He complained that no Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates could join the fleet.
The National Trust monitors the secret lives of the bats.
A new study conducted at a mansion in the Scottish Highlands aims to determine how flies use the landscape when hunting.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation efforts.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow the common sticks and brown arrowhead water lilies at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be installed at key locations in the mansion to track the activity of the bats during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all the records will determine the frequency of the calls of the bats and the species that emit them.
A map of their habitat and a report will be drawn up to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dwyer, a conservation advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important to the flies and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. the creation of meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
The population of flies in Scotland and the UK as a whole has declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction activities that affect their shelters and lead to habitat loss.
Population risks may be from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and certain chemical processing of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Actually, flies are not blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation techniques to detect insects and obstacles along their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 historic gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The Trust has trained experts who conduct regular surveys, asylum inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organisation has even set up the first and only special fleas reserve in Scotland at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galway, which is home to eight out of Scotland's ten species of fleas.
The mansion manager, David Thompson, says it's the perfect territory for them.
"Here in Threave, we have a great ground for flies", he noted.
We have old buildings, very old trees and a finished suitable habitat.
But there's a lot more about flies that we don't know, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.
It stresses the importance of checking for flies before property maintenance activities are carried out, as the unintentional destruction of a shelter is likely to kill up to 400 female and young flies and to destroy an entire local population.
Flies are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their shelters.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish fly conservation official, encourages the community to help.
She said, "I still have a lot to learn about our flies and about many of our animal species, because we just don't know what happens to their populations".
